Photo: Andy Lyons, Getty Images Image 39 of 39 San Antonio's Sebastien de La Cruz's competition is an African-American corrido singer in Compton 1 / 39 Back to Gallery San Antonio’s little mariachi, Sebastien de la Cruz, could meet his match in a young man named El Compa Negro, who sings straight out of Compton, Calif.
Not only can they both belt out songs in Spanish, Sebastien and El Compa, whose real name is Rhyan Lowery, have created a social media buzz in their own respects.
A few years ago San Antonio's little mariachi, who is a Mexican-American, was the target of racist remarks made by people who didn’t believe he should have sung America’s National Anthem a few at a San Antonio Spurs Finals game. Ethnicity has played a part in Lowery’s musical career, too. He told We Are Mitu he has “haters,” who don’t believe he should sing Mexican music, as an African American.
“He’s a lot more Mexican than I am, he’s legit,” Lowery's manager Antonio Lopez said in an interview with mySA.com. “There’s a value in what you choose to be rather than what you were born to be, people should respect that.”
RELATED: S.A.’s 'Little Mariachi’ drama to bow on ESPN
“Yo soy negro, claro. Afroamericano. Corazón y alma de un Mexicano,” he told the site, meaning that although he is black, he feels he has the heart and soul of a Mexican.
He told Estrella TV how he became an honorary member of the community when he crashed his neighbor’s norteño band practice session. Lowery started playing drums with the group, then became the front man of his own band — El Compa Negro and Los Mas Poderosos.
As he serenades groups of fans with his Spanish ballads, his presence on social media and within the realm of accordions and Cowboy hats grows. Lowery floods his Instagram profile with photos of recent concerts and meet ups with his fellow norteño singers.
"I don't think he knows how much value he has," Lopez said. "He's talented, he's natural, he's not trying to be something he's not."
